Japan, India, South Korea, Philippines: Asia Bonds and Currency Preview

-- B y   V .   R a m a k r i s h n a n
-- 
2011-05-15T22:48:26Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-15/japan-india-south-korea-philippines-asia-bonds-and-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in  Asia ’s bonds and currencies
today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the previous
trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary Yukio Edano will hold media
briefings at 11 a.m. and 4 p.m. in  Tokyo .  The Cabinet Office is set to report the nation’s machine
orders for March at 8:50 a.m. in Tokyo. Orders, an indicator of
business investment in three to six months, fell 10 percent
after dropping 2.3 percent in February, according to the median
estimate of economists in a Bloomberg News survey.  The Cabinet office will release at 2 p.m. in Tokyo its
report on Japan’s consumer confidence in April. The confidence
index slid to 36.7 from 38.6 in March, another survey showed.  The yield on the 1.3 percent government bond due March 2021
was 1.105 percent, according to  Japan  Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  India : Wholesale prices rose 8.40 percent in April from a
year earlier, compared with 8.98 percent in March, according to
the median estimate of economists in a Bloomberg survey before
data due today.  The yield on the 7.80 percent bond due April 2021 was 8.27
percent. The rupee was at 44.87 per dollar.  South Korea : The government will sell 1.6 trillion won
($1.5 billion) of 10-year bonds today. The central bank will
sell 1 trillion won of 91-day notes and 500 billion won of 182-
day notes.  The yield on South Korea’s 3 percent bond due December 2013
was 3.65 percent. The won was at 1,086.80 per dollar.  Philippines : The government will sell a combined 9 billion
pesos ($209 million) of 91-, 182- and 364-day bills today.  The yield on the 6.25 percent bond due April 2021 was 6.40
percent, according to Tradition Financial Services. The peso was
at 43.14 per dollar.  To contact the reporter on this story:
